result.execSummary:
The defendant Uniqua N. Vaughn was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Narcotic Drugs, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

No alcohol.  No illegal drugs or drug paraphernalia. Not to operate a motor vehicle without a valid driver's license. Not to go into any premises that the defendant knows contains illegal drugs. 
-------------------------------------

-------------------------------------
AODA assessment and follow through with recommendations.

timeConds.notes: The defendant is to complete eighty (80) hours of community service work during EACH year of her three (3) year term of probation for a total of two-hundred and forty (240) hours in and to the benefit of Walworth County with NO BUYOUT.

9:13 am  Court in session.  Case called.  Appearances given.  
Daniel A. Necci appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Defendant Uniqua N. Vaughn in court, in custody with attorney Michael John Fitzsimmons.  
Matter is before the Court for sentencing after revocation of probation.  
Also present is Defendant's Mother Ms. Lisa Vaughn and her Grandmother Ms. Donna Vaughn.  
9:13 am  Court makes record with regard to compelled statements of the deft included in the revocation packet.
The Court did not review the Revocation Summary because of this.  Attorneys advise that they do not have an agreement as to sentence.   
9:14 am  Attorney Fitzsimmons would prefer that the information be redacted.  
9:15 am  Both Attorneys believe the Court needs to read the revocation summary.  
The Court will reschedule the sentencing hearing and ask that the Court Commissioner review and redact any compelled statements of the Deft contained in the revocation packet submitted by the Agent.  
9:16 am  Discussion concerning sentence credit.  Attorney Fitzsimmons advises that there was presentence credit that was not reflected on the original Judgment of Conviction.  There is also a difference in the dates shown on the revocation order and warrant and those reflected on the sentence credit form obtained from the Walworth County Jail.  
9:19 am  Court asks if parties are comfortable with advising what their recommendations for sentence would be.
Defense would argue that the Court adopt the recommendation of the Probation Agent.  State would argue for 18 months of initial confinement followed by 2 years of extended supervision.
Court reschedules sentencing after revocation hearing.  Sentencing hearing on revocation scheduled for February 26, 2016 at 02:30 pm.
